CARMEN XIII.

This ode is like the ninth of the first book,-—a convivial song written in winter. A political allusion is extracted from v. 7 as from v. 9 of the other ode, and in either case we may suppose it possible that the troubles of the times are included in those anxieties which were to be left to the gods. But this proves nothing as to time, except that they were both written before the close of the civil wars, which is certain as respects this ode, and very probable as to the other. There can be little doubt of the subject as well ns the metre being imitated from the Greek. The reference to Achilles reminds us of C. i. 7,

and the allusion to Teucer. There is a fragment of Anacreon (6 Bergk) which bears some likeness to the opening of this Epode :—

ARGUMENT.

The tempest is raging, let us make merry, my friends, while we are young,v and leave the rest to the gods who will give us a good turn yet.
